1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,200
Stablecoin payments have one problem
nobody talks about — they're final.

2
00:00:04,200 --> 00:00:09,000
You pay, and if the merchant never
delivers, that's it. Your money's gone.

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,500
No chargeback. No recourse. That's the
wall between crypto and real commerce.

4
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:18,000
HSP fixed settlement — it made payments
verifiable and final.

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:22,500
Great for trust. But finality is exactly
what scares buyers off.

6
00:00:22,500 --> 00:00:28,000
Look around this hackathon: everyone adds
control before money moves.

7
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:33,000
Approvals, KYC, spend limits. Nobody gives
you a way back after.

8
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:36,500
That's the lane Kembali owns.

9
00:00:36,500 --> 00:00:41,500
And Kembali isn't just another escrow app —
it's a new primitive.

10
00:00:41,500 --> 00:00:45,000
Deterministic, arbiter-free recourse.

11
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:50,500
Every other escrow needs someone to judge
whether delivery happened.

12
00:00:50,500 --> 00:00:55,000
An oracle, a human, an AI arbiter, a bond
game. We removed all of it.

13
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:00,500
Because the deliverable lives on-chain,
"delivered" isn't an opinion —

14
00:01:00,500 --> 00:01:04,000
it's a fact the contract checks itself.

15
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:09,500
Your payment sits in escrow, bound to an
on-chain deliverable and a deadline.

16
00:01:09,500 --> 00:01:14,000
Merchant delivers the exact asset —
atomic swap, funds released.

17
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Merchant doesn't — after the deadline,
your money comes back. Kembali.

18
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:24,000
Let me show you — all of this is live on
HashKey mainnet. Real transactions.

19
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:28,500
First the happy path: an atomic
delivery-versus-payment.

20
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:33,500
The buyer opens an escrow — one click
approves the stablecoin,

21
00:01:33,500 --> 00:01:38,500
the next signs an EIP-712 HSP mandate
right in the wallet.

22
00:01:38,500 --> 00:01:43,000
That signature's digest is the payment ID.
Funds are now held on-chain.

23
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:48,500
Now I switch to the merchant's wallet —
approve the deliverable, hit Fulfill.

24
00:01:48,500 --> 00:01:54,500
In one transaction the asset goes to the
buyer and the funds release to the merchant.

25
00:01:54,500 --> 00:02:00,000
No middleman ever touched it. Withdraw,
and the status reads RELEASED.

26
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:05,500
Now the part that matters — what if the
merchant never delivers?

27
00:02:05,500 --> 00:02:10,500
Fresh escrow, short window. If the buyer
tries to refund now, it reverts.

28
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:15,500
TOO_EARLY. The buyer can't rug the merchant
mid-window — it's enforced on-chain.

29
00:02:15,500 --> 00:02:21,000
We let the window pass, and now refund
goes through.

30
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Buyer withdraws — status REFUNDED.
The money came back.

31
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
That's the recourse HSP alone
doesn't give you.

32
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Next — agent-safe commerce.
This is the AI-meets-DeFi piece.

33
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:42,000
The escrow always pulls funds from whoever
signed the mandate — not whoever submits it.

34
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:47,500
So an agent, or a relayer, can place a buy
on your behalf and can't redirect a cent.

35
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:53,000
We proved it live: one wallet signs,
a different agent wallet submits,

36
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:58,000
and the funds come out of the signer.
The agent pays gas and nothing else.

37
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:02,000
An agent literally cannot rug you.

38
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:07,500
And for regulated settlement — HashKey's
whole thesis — compliance is on-chain.

39
00:03:07,500 --> 00:03:13,500
CompliantEscrow checks the buyer's KYC and
sanctions attestations in an on-chain registry.

40
00:03:13,500 --> 00:03:18,500
A hard require, before the escrow can even
open. No attestation, it reverts.

41
00:03:18,500 --> 00:03:23,500
Not a checkbox in some backend — it's the
EVM saying no.

42
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:27,500
Compliant and reversible, both on-chain.

43
00:03:27,500 --> 00:03:32,500
Under all of this is audit-grade
engineering.

44
00:03:32,500 --> 00:03:38,500
Seventy-two tests, plus an invariant that
runs half a million random operations —

45
00:03:38,500 --> 00:03:42,500
and proves the money can never leak.

46
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:47,500
Fifteen end-to-end tests drive this live
dApp with real mainnet transactions.

47
00:03:47,500 --> 00:03:53,000
The canonical HSP payment ID is hashed and
verified on-chain, matching the reference SDK.

48
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,500
And the deployed bytecode is a byte-for-byte
match to the audited source. We checked.

49
00:03:58,500 --> 00:04:02,000
Nothing here is a mock.

50
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:07,000
So that's Kembali. Everyone else built a
gate in front of the payment.

51
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:12,500
We built the door back out — trustlessly,
HSP-native, live on HashKey Chain.

52
00:04:12,500 --> 00:04:16,500
Payments that can come back.
